#+TITLE: docs: content gaps to fill (contracts, algorithms, thread-safety)
#+DATE: 2026-06-20

* DONE [#B] Write the missing documentation content  :doc:content:
  RESOLUTION (2026-06-20): Wrote doc/common.org (exported to pdf/html/info/man
  by the doc toolchain) covering the cross-cutting material that was missing:
  - Whole-tree: a thread-safety statement and a build/usage quickstart.
  - bclib: the BcExcept TRY/RAISE contract (balanced TRY/ENDTRY, thread-local
    chain, BcRETURN* rules) and the data1/data2 "integer-through-a-pointer"
    payload convention; the BcCStr static-buffer caveat.
  - benlib: the PostScript char-name vocabulary (the central concept), a worked
    conversion example, the "same name per code point" and sorted-approxim-table
    rules, and the supported encodings.
  - bplib/bolib: the ownership / reference-counting contract (init => useCount 0
    owned by the delete pool; retain/release balance; over-release raises;
    returned objects are pool-owned; when to drain; the assign() macro;
    BoList vs BoListNoRetain).
  - bprib: the mod-97 RIB key formula with a worked example (-> 06).
  - bpcombi: the lazy getNextElement/done protocol and the cardinal() formulae.
  Also fixed the stale BoArray.h resize: precondition (done with bolib-bugs) and
  the bjlib doc typos noted there.
  Per-module standalone .org files can be split out later; for now a single
  umbrella document carries the content and builds cleanly.

The per-function header comments are unusually good (PRE/POST/RETURN/RAISE).
What's missing is the *cross-cutting* documentation a user needs to use each
library safely. Capture these in the per-module =.org= files (see
[[file:doc-toolchain-orgmode.issue][doc-toolchain-orgmode]]).

** Whole-tree
- *Thread-safety statement.* Nothing documents that several pieces of mutable
  global state are unsynchronised: =BcExcept= TRY-chain, =BcCStr= static return
  buffers, =BcRandom= seed file, bplib/bolib delete pools. State plainly:
  "single-threaded unless noted."
- *Build/usage quickstart*: =make depend; make; make install=, default
  =PREFIX=/usr/local=, module dependency order, =sudo make install=.

** bclib
- The =BcExcept= TRY/RAISE/HANDLER contract: balanced =BcTRY=/=BcENDTRY=, the
  rule that =BcRETURN*= may only be used inside a live TRY, and that it is not
  reentrant/thread-safe (see [[file:bclib-exceptions-and-globals.issue][bclib-exceptions-and-globals]]).
- The =data1/data2= exception payload convention: values are stuffed into
  =void*= via =(void*)(CARDPTR)x= and are *not pointers* — handlers must reverse
  the cast. Currently only cryptic =/* CARD32 size,NIL */= comments.
- =BcCStr= size-vs-length semantics (the off-by-one bug came from this being
  unclear) and the non-reentrant static-buffer return convention.

** benlib
- The *char-name vocabulary* (PostScript glyph names used as the interchange
  key) — the single most important concept for using or extending the library —
  is undocumented. Add the list and the "add a new encoding" recipe.
- Provenance/layout of the exotic encodings (Honeywell 200/600 SSF, Univac
  Field Data, IBM BCD, EBCDIC variant): bit/column basis, octal codes, source.
- A full worked conversion example (=BenMode_*=, replacement-string semantics).

** bplib / bolib
- *The ownership / refcounting contract* — the most error-prone part and only in
  scattered comments. State: =init= yields useCount 0 owned by the delete pool
  (autorelease-like); first =retain= removes it; balanced retain/release; who
  owns returned objects (e.g. =BpDict::allKeys= returns a non-retained pooled
  object); when to call =processReleasePool=/=processDeletePool=; exception
  safety of mutators. Document the =assign(var,value)= macro.
- =BoList= vs =BoListNoRetain= choice criteria and the dangling-pointer risk.

** bprib / bpcombi
- RIB mod-97 key algorithm: the formula (concatenate banque+guichet+compte+"00",
  letter→digit substitution, key =(97-(N mod 97)) mod 97=), *why*, a worked
  example, and a reference to the French RIB / IBAN standard.
- Combinatorial enumeration: the lazy =getNextElement=/=done= protocol, the
  state machine in =BpArrangementSansRepeat::step=, valid ranges for
  =baseCardinal=/=elementSize=, and the =_cardinal= overflow limits.

** Stale doc to fix while here
- =BoArray.h:60-68= =resize:= PRE contradicts the code (says no-shrink; code
  shrinks). Several =bjlib= header contracts are copy-paste stale (e.g.
  =bjstring_search_forward= doc says "backward"; =bjstring_set_format_va=
  actually appends and self-notes "we should change the name").

** Plan
Fill these as the =doc/*.org= files are written; treat the ownership/refcount
contract and the benlib char-name vocabulary as the two highest-value pieces.
